{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17520280","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17520280"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:21:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:21:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13172"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13172","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13172"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.27,0.18,0.22,0.32,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5609"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109436"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5609","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5609"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13172"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91805"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"7940"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9539"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9671"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35172"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37279"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40875"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109436","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109436"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 76-year-old man presented with a two day history of a tender rash on his face (image). He denies a history of any similar eruptions. His medical history includes type 2 diabetes, hypertension and benign prostatic hyperplasia. His current medications include tamsulosin, metformin, glipizide and amlodipine. He has no known allergies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination his blood pressure is 134/76 mmHg, pulse 82/min and temperature 37.8\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC. There is no exudate, and there are no bullae or vesicles present. There is a clear demarcation between the affected and unaffected areas of the skin, and the affected region appears raised. The affected areas are warm to touch. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["No treatment required","Mupirocin 2% ointment","Intravenous penicillin V","Oral flucloxacillin","Intravenous vancomycin"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is suffering from erysipelas, which is characterised by the classic involvement of the face in a \u0022butterfly\u0022 pattern, a raised border and a clear demarcation between the infected and uninfected tissue. Erysipelas is commonly observed in infants, young children and older adults. It most commonly affects the lower limbs, but when involving the face has the typical butterfly distribution as in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDistinguishing between cellulitis and erysipelas can be challenging since both conditions present as spreading areas of skin erythema. Cellulitis is an infection of the deep dermis and subcutaneous fat; erysipelas is more superficial, involving only the upper dermis and superficial lymphatics. Cellulitis may present with or without purulence; erysipelas is nonpurulent. Cellulitis is an acute spreading infection of the skin with visually indistinct borders; in erysipelas, there is clear demarcation between involved and uninvolved tissue.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPatients with cellulitis or erysipelas require management with antibiotic therapy. In most cases of erysipelas and those without systemic features, \u003Cstrong\u003Eoral flucloxacillin\u003C/strong\u003E (aka phenoxymethylpenicillin) or dicloxacillin can be prescribed in an outpatient setting. This regimen would be suitable for this particular patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf patients exhibit systemic signs of toxicity, such as high fever, tachycardia, hypotension, or confusion,\u003Cstrong\u003E intravenous antibiotics \u003C/strong\u003Esuch as \u003Cstrong\u003Eflucloxacillin \u003C/strong\u003Eor benzylpenicillin should be initiated. Patients at a higher risk of MRSA infection should be treated with \u003Cstrong\u003Eintravenous vancomycin\u003C/strong\u003E. While \u003Cstrong\u003Etopical antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E can be effective for certain skin infections (e.g., impetigo, folliculitis), they are unlikely to be effective for cellulitis or erysipelas due to the involvement of deeper skin layers beyond the epidermis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Erysipelas is characterised by the classic involvement of the face in a \u0022butterfly\u0022 pattern, a raised border, and a clear demarcation between the infected and uninfected tissue.","Most cases of erysipelas can be treated with oral antibiotic in an outpatient setting."],"references":["Sukumaran V, Senanayake S. Bacterial skin and soft tissue infections. Aust Prescr [Internet]. 2016 Oct [cited 2023 Jul 9];39(5):159. Available from: https://www.nps.org.au/australian-prescriber/articles/bacterial-skin-and-soft-tissue-infections doi: 10.18773/austprescr.2016.058","Brindle R, Williams M, Barton E, et al. Assessment of Antibiotic Treatment of Cellulitis and Erysipelas A Systematic Review and Meta-analysis. JAMA Dermatol. 2019; 155:1033-40."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91805"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13172"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20294"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20294","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20294"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/OkdDP3Mp89Oe2bOCSBNakBqlXdSxgA.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/OkdDP3Mp